@@eThe Forest of Confusion -- Wall Command Operational Report@@N

This is not a distant threat assessment. This is @@dWall Command's@@N
most active operational theater. The Forest of Confusion begins
north of our walls, where patrol roads fail under forces older
than Kiess, older than Evermeet.

Three systems collide here. @@yKiess civic order@@N pushes outward with
patrol roads, waystones, and bell-posts. The @@gVerdant ecological
intelligence@@N produces chemical disorientation and selective path-
rerouting. And @@dWithered Conclave residue@@N -- crystal-hum, fungal
geometry, deteriorating quarantine wards -- weaponizes disorientation
into attritional hazard.

The @@rconfusion mists@@N were not natural. Druids engineered them to
contain crystal matrices the @@WSpirebound Conclave@@N embedded in the
forest's roots and then @@rabandoned@@N. The Conclave again -- the same
sealed-warrant authority whose obsidian disc we found in Evermeet's
ruins. They installed infrastructure, extracted what they wanted,
and left the consequences. The druids contained it for centuries,
then their order died demographically. The mists lost calibrated
purpose and diffused outward.

Wall Command manages the @@rsymptoms@@N. Our @@yrope-line corridors@@N are
anchored between iron stakes driven deep enough to resist root
displacement. @@yBell-posts@@N at quarter-mile intervals sound in
patterns that cut through acoustic distortion. Paired patrol teams
with mandatory check-ins. No solo patrols. No deviation from
rope-lines without command authorization.

The @@rmist incursion contracts the safe perimeter each season.@@N
Three years ago the northern bell-post line held at the ridge.
Last season we lost two posts to root displacement and one to
crystal resonance. This season's perimeter is tighter.

@@gTreants@@N guard as sentinels. @@eCentaurs@@N maintain armed neutrality,
their oral tradition preserving accounts we record when offered.
@@rNeogi@@N slavers exploit the fog. Deep in the wood, @@rYmmas@@N
occupies a cabin that root growth has never reclaimed.

The @@yTrade Syndics@@N fund northern operations because the forest
sits between Kiess and the @@gVerdant Depths@@N. If the rope-line
corridors fail, we lose northern access entirely.

@@dThe Prism remembers@@N: three institutions failed in sequence. The
Conclave created the problem. The druids contained it. Kiess
manages what remains. We are the third attempt, and we are losing
ground. The question is whether we adapt faster than the mist.
